That's a clever effect you're looking to achieve! To make a text in HTML stay stationary while its visibility fades into view from left to right, you can use CSS animations and keyframe rules.

Here's an example:

HTML:
```html
<p class="fade-in-text">Your text here</p>
```
CSS:
```css
.fade-in-text {
  position: relative;
  opacity: 0;
  transform: translateX(-100%);
}

.fade-in-text.animate {
  animation: fade-in 2s forwards;
}

@keyframes fade-in {
  0% {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateX(-100%);
  }
  100% {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: translateX(0);
  }
}
```
In this example, we're using the `translateX` property to move the text off-screen to the left initially, and then animating it to move to its original position while increasing the opacity. You can adjust the animation duration and timing function to suit your needs.

To trigger the animation, you can add the `animate` class to the element using JavaScript. For example:

JavaScript:
```javascript
const textElement = document.querySelector('.fade-in-text');
textElement.classList.add('animate');
```
This will start the animation, making the text fade in from left to right.

